                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>WILLIAM SUMMERFIELD. I am a watchman of Mary-le-bone. On the 11th of January, at a quarter before seven o'clock in the morning, I was in <placeName id="t18290115-253-crimeloc1360">Adam-street, Westminster</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290115-253-crimeloc1360" type="placeName" value="Adam-street, Westminster"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290115-253-crimeloc1360" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290115-253-off1358 t18290115-253-crimeloc1360"></join>- I watched the premises of Mr. Martin, a <rs id="t18290115-253-viclabel1361" type="occupation">stable-keeper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290115-253-victim1926 t18290115-253-viclabel1361"></join>, in consequence of information, and saw the two prisoners cross Upper Berkley-street, which is two or three hundred yards from Mr. Martin's - they were in company, and coming towards me; I am positive they are the two men: Smith was carrying something - I went and clapped my hand upon his shoulder, and said,</p>
               <p>"You are the very fellow I want;" I took these eight glasses from under his arm - Hilbert immediately decamped; I called for assistance and gave Smith into custody - Hilbert ran into Upper Seymour-street; I ran and took him as he was stooping as if going to tie his shoe - I am confident he was with Smith.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290115-253-person1927">
                  WILLIAM 
                  GOROON
               <interp inst="t18290115-253-person1927" type="surname" value="GOROON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290115-253-person1927" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290115-253-person1927" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a gas-lighter. On Sunday morning, the 11th of January, at a quarter before seven o'clock, I saw the two prisoners in the news and gave information to the watchman - Smith asked me what o'clock it was.</p>
               <p>WATKINS WILLIAM MARTIN. I am a liverystablekeeper - my stable is in the mews; these four glasses are my property - they were in post-chaises which were standing in the mews; I have no doubt they are mine - one is broken and the piece of it is left behind; they would cost me about 8l.</p>
               <p>SMITH'S Defence. I was passing by the mews, and saw two young men pass with these glasses under their arms- they went to a watch-box, returned and placed them against the side of the mews, and when the watchman came by, they went to a watch-box, returned and placed them against the side of the mews, and when the watchman came by, they decamped; I staid till be passed, and then I must own I was going to take away the glasses.</p>
               <p>SMITH - <rs id="t18290115-253-verdict1362" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290115-253-verdict1362" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 23.</p>
               <p>HILBERT - <rs id="t18290115-253-verdict1363" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290115-253-verdict1363" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 17.</p>
